{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0c1b4333-8a8e-4b97-a4be-6273a4c2277b","content":"For a CPU-pegged .NET 8 service on Windows, **dotnet-trace** is the quickest option:\n\n```powershell\n# Install (one-time)\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your process\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect ~30s of CPU sampling data\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or **PerfView**.\n\n**If you need deeper ETW-level data** (kernel stacks, context switches), use [PerfView](https://github.com/microsoft/perfview/releases) instead:\n\n```powershell\nPerfView.exe collect -Duration:30 -CircularMB:500 -ThreadTime\n```\n\n**Recommendation:** Start with `dotnet-trace` — it's lower overhead and gives you managed call stacks immediately. Escalate to PerfView if you suspect native code, thread contention, or need kernel-level insight.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a74cd80f-9013-4f5f-9a9d-727d9b78a6bd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question - they don't need me to modify code or run commands in their environment. I'll give them a concise, practical answer.\n\nThe best tool for this scenario is `dotnet-trace` or PerfView. For CPU profiling specifically on Windows:\n\n1. **dotnet-trace** - cross-platform, lightweight, built into the .NET SDK tooling\n2. **PerfView** - Windows-specific, more powerful, uses ETW\n\nFor a CPU-pegged scenario, `dotnet-trace` with the `cpu-sampling` profile is the quickest path. \n\nPerfView gives you more detailed analysis but requires more setup, so I'll focus on the simpler `dotnet-trace` approach first and mention PerfView as an alternative if they need deeper diagnostics.","outputTokens":447,"requestId":"C3D7:31353F:1CA266E:203EF84:6A07C22D"},"id":"c79b1ace-de51-4afd-bac0-